In article <PHR.93Feb11123103@napa.telebit.com> phr@telebit.com (Paul Rubin) writes:
>In article <1993Feb9.191702.6416@ulysses.att.com> smb@research.att.com (Steven Bellovin) writes:
>
>   Anyway, it's now been proven that DES is not a group.  There is still
>   a variant on exhaustive search that works on double encryption, but it
>   takes a lot of memory.  Most folks recommend triple encryption, with
>   two keys, and the second step a decryption using the second key.  The
>   first and third steps use the first key.
>
>Martin Hellman recommended using 3 independent keys in his DES
>talk at the recent RSA data security conference.

For an implementation look at Richard Outerbridge's d3des.
It is included with RIPEM. Alternatively it is available
from ghost.dsi.unimi.it in /pub/crypt

